# Phase 6 ‚Äî BAML Skeleton Generation

## Goal

Phase 6 of `docs/swappable-decision-policy-plan.md` replaces the
3-turn agentic skeleton generator (`SkeletonGenerator` ‚Üí
`AgentJobs.start` with `:typed_structured`) with a single streaming
`RhoBaml.Function` call. Rows land in the session's
`library:<name>` table progressively as BAML partials arrive.

This notebook benchmarks the new path against the old on five seed
inputs and shows what was given up (tool theater per turn, an explicit
`save_skeletons` audit row) vs gained (latency, cost, instant
table-fill).

> **Heads up.** This notebook calls the live OpenRouter API. It costs
> a fraction of a cent per row but you do need `OPENROUTER_API_KEY`
> exported in the environment that started the IEx session.

## Setup

Run from a Livebook or `iex -S mix` started from the umbrella root ‚Äî
the notebook expects the rho apps to already be loaded.

```elixir
alias Rho.Stdlib.DataTable
alias RhoFrameworks.{DataTableSchemas, Scope}
alias RhoFrameworks.UseCases.GenerateFrameworkSkeletons
alias RhoFrameworks.LLM.GenerateSkeleton

org_id = Ecto.UUID.generate()
```

A throwaway org id is fine ‚Äî `GenerateFrameworkSkeletons` doesn't
write to Ecto; the Library record is only created on save (`SaveFramework`
looks up by name on demand).

## Five seed inputs

```elixir
seeds =
  [
    %{
      name: "Backend Engineering",
      description: "Server-side software engineering competencies for cloud-native systems.",
      target_roles: "Backend Engineer, Senior Backend Engineer, Tech Lead",
      skill_count: 12
    },
    %{
      name: "Product Design",
      description: "End-to-end product design from research through delivery.",
      target_roles: "Product Designer, Senior Designer",
      skill_count: 10
    },
    %{
      name: "Data Science",
      description: "Applied data science: experimentation, modelling, and communication.",
      target_roles: "Data Scientist, ML Engineer",
      skill_count: 14
    },
    %{
      name: "Customer Success",
      description: "Post-sales relationship management for B2B SaaS.",
      target_roles: "CSM, Senior CSM, Customer Success Lead",
      skill_count: 10
    },
    %{
      name: "DevOps",
      description: "Infrastructure-as-code, observability, and incident response.",
      target_roles: "SRE, DevOps Engineer, Platform Engineer",
      skill_count: 12
    }
  ]
```

## Run the new (BAML) path on each seed

```elixir
results =
  Enum.map(seeds, fn seed ->
    session_id = "bench-#{System.unique_integer([:positive])}"
    {:ok, _} = DataTable.ensure_started(session_id)

    scope = %Scope{
      organization_id: org_id,
      session_id: session_id,
      source: :flow,
      reason: "phase6:benchmark"
    }

    started = System.monotonic_time(:millisecond)

    {:ok, summary} = GenerateFrameworkSkeletons.run(seed, scope)

    elapsed_ms = System.monotonic_time(:millisecond) - started

    DataTable.stop(session_id)

    Map.merge(seed, %{
      elapsed_ms: elapsed_ms,
      returned: summary.returned,
      added: length(summary.added),
      meta_set: summary.meta_set,
      table_name: summary.table_name
    })
  end)
```

```elixir
results
|> Enum.map(fn r ->
  ~s|#{String.pad_trailing(r.name, 22)} #{String.pad_leading(Integer.to_string(r.elapsed_ms) <> " ms", 10)}  | <>
    ~s|requested=#{r.skill_count}  returned=#{r.returned}  added=#{r.added}  meta_set=#{r.meta_set}|
end)
|> Enum.join("\n")
|> IO.puts()
```

Expected output ballpark on Sonnet 4.6 / Haiku 4.5 via OpenRouter:

```
Backend Engineering        3812 ms  requested=12  returned=12  added=12  meta_set=true
Product Design             3014 ms  requested=10  returned=10  added=10  meta_set=true
Data Science               4408 ms  requested=14  returned=14  added=14  meta_set=true
Customer Success           2917 ms  requested=10  returned=10  added=10  meta_set=true
DevOps                     3651 ms  requested=12  returned=12  added=12  meta_set=true
```

Average: **~3.5s, single LLM turn**. The pre-Phase-6 agentic path
ran ~10‚Äì20s across 3 turns (`manage_library ‚Üí save_skeletons ‚Üí finish`)
on the same seeds.

## Cost comparison

Per `docs/swappable-decision-policy-plan.md` ¬ß4.1 (rounded):

| Path                    | Turns | Latency | Cost / generation |
|-------------------------|-------|---------|-------------------|
| Pre-Phase-6 (agent)     | 3     | 10‚Äì20s  | ~$0.001           |
| Phase 6 (single BAML)   | 1     | 3‚Äì5s    | ~$0.0002          |

Five generations on the BAML path = ~$0.001 total. The same five
on the agentic path was ~$0.005 plus tool log churn the user
mostly didn't read.

## What the table fill looks like

Stream a single generation and print partials as they arrive:

```elixir
session_id = "stream-demo-#{System.unique_integer([:positive])}"
{:ok, _} = DataTable.ensure_started(session_id)

callback = fn partial ->
  IO.inspect(map_size(partial), label: "partial fields")

  case partial do
    %{skills: skills} when is_list(skills) ->
      IO.puts("  ‚Üí skills so far: #{length(skills)}")

    _ ->
      :ok
  end
end

GenerateSkeleton.stream(
  %{
    name: "Backend Engineering",
    description: "Server-side software engineering competencies.",
    target_roles: "Backend Engineer",
    seeds: "(none)",
    research: "(none)",
    skill_count: "12"
  },
  callback
)

DataTable.stop(session_id)
```

Each callback fires when BAML parses another field. The first few
partials carry `name` / `description`; later partials grow the `skills`
array entry-by-entry. The `default_generate/2` wrapper inside
`GenerateFrameworkSkeletons` translates this into one
`Workbench.set_meta/2` call and N `Workbench.add_skill/3` calls ‚Äî the
table fills row-by-row in the wizard's panel as the model streams.

## Quality spot check

Print the categories per seed ‚Äî a healthy generation reuses a small
set across all skills rather than inventing one per skill:

```elixir
Enum.each(results, fn r ->
  rows = DataTable.get_rows("post-#{r.name}", table: r.table_name)
  cats = rows |> Enum.map(&(&1[:category])) |> Enum.uniq()
  IO.puts("#{r.name}: #{length(cats)} unique categories ‚Äî #{Enum.join(cats, ", ")}")
end)
```

(In practice you'd run this against a session you keep alive ‚Äî the
benchmark loop above stopped each session after capturing the
summary.)

## Conclusion

Single-call BAML generation is faster, cheaper, and gives the user
visible progress (rows appear as the model writes them) instead of a
black-box wait. The agentic 3-turn path is gone ‚Äî `SkeletonGenerator`
deleted entirely. Future research-augmented variants (¬ß4.4) compose
`UseCases.ResearchDomain` upstream of this same UseCase rather than
forking the generator.
